Generally higher budgets will come from larger publishers.

76
00:05:16,559 --> 00:05:19,080
Larger publishers tend to be a little bit more unwavering

77
00:05:19,540 --> 00:05:20,801
in their ability to negotiate

78
00:05:20,881 --> 00:05:22,661
or will to negotiate their publishing terms.

79
00:05:24,282 --> 00:05:25,862
If this is your first game,

80
00:05:26,543 --> 00:05:28,303
then you can definitely expect to be low board

81
00:05:28,343 --> 00:05:29,744
in terms of the commercial legals.

82
00:05:30,484 --> 00:05:32,305
And they'll generally be seen,

83
00:05:32,445 --> 00:05:34,485
you'll generally be seen as a higher risk prospect

84
00:05:34,846 --> 00:05:37,487
or signing to a publisher's existing portfolio.

85
00:05:39,391 --> 00:05:41,473
However, projects that are in the latest stage of development

86
00:05:41,893 --> 00:05:43,154
will tend to be seen as lower risk,

87
00:05:43,755 --> 00:05:45,936
as generally the publisher's upfront costs will be lower.

88
00:05:46,877 --> 00:05:49,139
That usually allows you to be able to negotiate

89
00:05:49,179 --> 00:05:50,740
better commercial and legal terms.

90
00:05:54,884 --> 00:05:56,445
So, what are the contract killers

91
00:05:56,465 --> 00:05:57,746
that I'm referring to in this talk?

92
00:05:59,287 --> 00:06:01,509
To me, these are terms in most publishing contracts

93
00:06:02,750 --> 00:06:04,592
that will invariably affect the developer

94
00:06:04,632 --> 00:06:05,472
in a negative way,

95
00:06:06,153 --> 00:06:07,574
especially in the event of a falling out

96
00:06:07,714 --> 00:06:08,515
between the parties.

97
00:06:09,430 --> 00:06:11,112
and even if the developer is not at fault.

98
00:06:12,373 --> 00:06:14,095
So some of the red flags we're going to look at include

99
00:06:14,595 --> 00:06:15,936
what's happening with your game IP

100
00:06:16,617 --> 00:06:18,459
and to do this we'll dive into

101
00:06:18,519 --> 00:06:20,841
what the difference between an intellectual property assignment

102
00:06:21,461 --> 00:06:22,823
and an intellectual property license.

103
00:06:24,164 --> 00:06:26,826
We'll then look at publishing licenses in a bit more detail

104
00:06:26,926 --> 00:06:28,648
and some of the bad license terms to look out for.

105
00:06:30,009 --> 00:06:32,051
And then we'll look at how you can get paid

106
00:06:32,872 --> 00:06:34,273
and some of the terms around that

107
00:06:34,373 --> 00:06:36,235
and some bad payment terms to look out for.

108
00:06:38,693 --> 00:06:42,115
So, Contract Killer 1, what is happening to your game IP?

109
00:06:43,376 --> 00:06:45,637
In particular, are you giving this away unwittingly?

110
00:06:47,318 --> 00:06:49,560
Publishing contracts will vary from publisher to publisher.

111
00:06:50,360 --> 00:06:53,743
However, most of these contracts will have at least one thing

112
00:06:53,783 --> 00:06:56,905
in common, and that is a clause giving the publisher the rights

113
00:06:56,925 --> 00:06:59,286
to publish, market, distribute, and otherwise

114
00:06:59,366 --> 00:07:02,728
export your game across various platforms and territories.

115
00:07:06,567 --> 00:07:08,589
Now a publisher needs this permission from a developer

116
00:07:08,909 --> 00:07:10,310
before they can actually publish your game.

117
00:07:10,331 --> 00:07:12,693
Yeah, obviously, I think that's probably

118
00:07:12,753 --> 00:07:13,473
quite an obvious statement.

119
00:07:13,753 --> 00:07:15,475
But this is because games are a bundle

120
00:07:15,515 --> 00:07:16,636
of intellectual property rights

121
00:07:17,477 --> 00:07:20,059
that you as the creator of the game, the developer will own.

122
00:07:21,120 --> 00:07:23,342
So obviously the publisher needs permission from you first

123
00:07:23,402 --> 00:07:24,703
before they can just go and publish it.

124
00:07:26,104 --> 00:07:27,606
Similar thing would happen

125
00:07:27,666 --> 00:07:29,287
if you wanted to use Mario in your game.

126
00:07:29,507 --> 00:07:31,309
You'd need to get permission from Nintendo to do that.

127
00:07:32,210 --> 00:07:33,671
Although that's quite unlikely, I'd say.

128
00:07:35,305 --> 00:07:43,770
This permission is normally detailed under the Grants of Rights section, but it might also be called the Operative Provision, Ownership, Publishing Licence or something like that.

129
00:07:45,251 --> 00:07:50,513
In each case, this Grants of Rights section will give the publisher the right to use the intellectual property rights in your game.

130
00:07:51,554 --> 00:07:54,215
The publishing contract might deal with this in a couple of ways.

131
00:07:55,623 --> 00:07:57,164
The first being an exclusive license.

132
00:07:57,704 --> 00:07:58,724
That's the most common way.

133
00:07:59,245 --> 00:08:00,365
And this will give the publisher the right

134
00:08:00,385 --> 00:08:02,286
to be the only person allowed to publish your game

135
00:08:03,026 --> 00:08:04,147
across various platforms

136
00:08:04,207 --> 00:08:05,608
in various countries around the world.

137
00:08:06,348 --> 00:08:08,169
And that would even stop you as the developer

138
00:08:08,189 --> 00:08:11,050
from self-publishing or from engaging any other party

139
00:08:11,110 --> 00:08:12,231
from doing any of those things.

140
00:08:13,531 --> 00:08:15,052
We'll refer to this exclusive license

141
00:08:15,372 --> 00:08:16,733
as the publishing license from here on out.

142
00:08:18,978 --> 00:08:21,218
The other option is an intellectual property assignment.

143
00:08:21,719 --> 00:08:24,479
And that's effectively where the publisher buys the IP

144
00:08:24,619 --> 00:08:25,680
or percentage of it off you.

145
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:30,201
It's arguable that the exclusive license approach is better,

146
00:08:31,101 --> 00:08:33,762
normally because publishing licenses are only temporary,

147
00:08:33,782 --> 00:08:34,962
so they might last for a few years

148
00:08:35,082 --> 00:08:36,483
before the rights revert back to you.

149
00:08:37,923 --> 00:08:40,564
But the worst case scenario

150
00:08:40,584 --> 00:08:42,564
for both the publishing license and an assignment

151
00:08:43,025 --> 00:08:44,625
is that you as the developer can't get the rights

152
00:08:44,685 --> 00:08:45,285
and you're getting back.

153
00:08:47,345 --> 00:08:49,186
that could obviously be a bit of a disaster,

154
00:08:49,226 --> 00:08:51,827
especially if you're planning on doing future games

155
00:08:52,247 --> 00:08:54,288
or have future plans for the game

156
00:08:54,328 --> 00:08:55,368
and the franchise you're making.

157
00:09:01,091 --> 00:09:02,912
So let's look at assignments in more detail.

158
00:09:03,952 --> 00:09:05,753
So how does an assignment work in the context

159
00:09:05,793 --> 00:09:07,074
of assigning rights in a video game?

160
00:09:08,954 --> 00:09:10,275
When people talk about assignments,

161
00:09:11,015 --> 00:09:12,796
they're really talking about transfer of ownership.

162
00:09:13,396 --> 00:09:14,677
So think of it like selling a car.

163
00:09:15,759 --> 00:09:19,162
Person A, the current owner of the car, sells the car to Person B for money.

164
00:09:19,803 --> 00:09:21,745
Naturally, Person B is now the new owner of the car.

165
00:09:22,145 --> 00:09:23,646
Person A can't then use it again.

166
00:09:24,507 --> 00:09:26,709
But they have been compensated by receiving money in return.

167
00:09:28,753 --> 00:09:33,857
For video games, the transfer and assignment we're talking about is that of all the intellectual property,

168
00:09:33,877 --> 00:09:39,501
I'm just going to refer to that as IP, that goes into the game, and any other materials relevant to the game itself.

169
00:09:40,242 --> 00:09:45,026
So the IP rights in a game being pretty much everything you can think about on the front end and back end.

170
00:09:45,546 --> 00:09:54,273
It might be the things that you can see, so the art, the animation or hear the music, but it might also be the things that you can't see, such as the code and anything in the back end.

171
00:09:55,854 --> 00:09:57,315
So in the context of a grant of rights,

172
00:09:57,975 --> 00:09:59,535
an assignment of IP in this instance,

173
00:10:00,095 --> 00:10:02,736
that being the IP that exists in the video game,

174
00:10:03,556 --> 00:10:05,017
is where the ownership of that game IP

175
00:10:05,357 --> 00:10:07,478
is legally transferred from the developer to the publisher.

176
00:10:09,218 --> 00:10:11,299
The publisher then has the rights in the game IP

177
00:10:11,339 --> 00:10:13,860
and can publish it, distribute it, create new versions,

178
00:10:13,900 --> 00:10:16,120
basically do anything it wants after that point.

179
00:10:18,078 --> 00:10:19,699
So how does this work in practice?

180
00:10:20,439 --> 00:10:22,140
Well, for a finished game, it's fairly straightforward.

181
00:10:22,640 --> 00:10:24,541
Developer assigns its IP rights in the game

182
00:10:24,561 --> 00:10:25,201
to the publisher.

183
00:10:25,921 --> 00:10:27,922
Publisher then takes those rights and publishes the game.

184
00:10:29,022 --> 00:10:30,723
The rights will be legally owned by the publisher.

185
00:10:30,943 --> 00:10:33,604
So yes, the developer will no longer own the IP,

186
00:10:34,584 --> 00:10:36,525
but it might still be paid a percentage

187
00:10:36,725 --> 00:10:38,125
from the sales of the game,

188
00:10:38,545 --> 00:10:40,666
or they might have received money up front as compensation.

189
00:10:42,544 --> 00:10:43,725
For a game that's still in development,

190
00:10:43,945 --> 00:10:45,546
it works pretty much a similar way,

191
00:10:46,187 --> 00:10:48,849
except that the developer will be deemed to have assigned IP

192
00:10:49,249 --> 00:10:51,891
as it delivers certain milestones or builds to the developer

193
00:10:52,472 --> 00:10:54,373
until effectively it's delivered a finished game,

194
00:10:54,573 --> 00:10:56,375
in which case all of the rights will then be deemed

195
00:10:56,395 --> 00:10:57,996
to be assigned over to the publisher.

196
00:11:00,018 --> 00:11:01,019
So same thing applies,

197
00:11:01,099 --> 00:11:02,280
publisher ends up with a finished game,

198
00:11:02,620 --> 00:11:03,861
it has all the rights into that game

199
00:11:03,921 --> 00:11:06,183
and then can do what it wants, including publishing it.

200
00:11:09,225 --> 00:11:10,146
An assignment of rights

201
00:11:11,238 --> 00:11:12,398
especially intellectual property rights

202
00:11:12,418 --> 00:11:13,659
that we discussed in this way,

203
00:11:13,959 --> 00:11:15,800
is far more common for worker for hire

204
00:11:15,860 --> 00:11:16,941
or contracted development.

205
00:11:17,441 --> 00:11:19,002
So if you're working on your own IP

206
00:11:19,442 --> 00:11:21,103
and talking about a publisher in that sense,

207
00:11:21,443 --> 00:11:23,425
then you probably don't want to assign these rights away.

208
00:11:24,985 --> 00:11:26,846
And you don't have to assign all of your IP rights.

209
00:11:27,627 --> 00:11:30,148
Some publishing contracts may only require a developer

210
00:11:30,168 --> 00:11:32,330
to assign part of its IP to the publisher.

211
00:11:33,230 --> 00:11:35,992
This is common in co-funded or co-development of agents

212
00:11:36,032 --> 00:11:37,252
between a developer and a publisher

213
00:11:37,773 --> 00:11:40,434
where both parties are putting in equal amounts of money.

214
00:11:42,538 --> 00:11:44,598
But co-ownership of IP can be messy.

215
00:11:45,339 --> 00:11:46,439
It's not like real property,

216
00:11:46,639 --> 00:11:48,860
so like houses, flats, buildings, and the like,

217
00:11:49,360 --> 00:11:51,300
where lines can easily be drawn about who owns what

218
00:11:51,320 --> 00:11:52,460
or who has access to what.

219
00:11:53,401 --> 00:11:55,681
Even giving away the smallest percentage of your IP

220
00:11:55,781 --> 00:11:57,482
can cause problems down the line,

221
00:11:58,102 --> 00:11:59,342
especially if you don't have the permission

222
00:11:59,382 --> 00:12:00,643
from the other party to use it.

223
00:12:02,743 --> 00:12:04,164
This will definitely cause a lot of issues

224
00:12:04,224 --> 00:12:06,264
or can cause a lot of issues in the event of a dispute,

225
00:12:06,364 --> 00:12:07,665
especially if you're the developer

226
00:12:07,945 --> 00:12:09,285
and you're naturally at a disadvantage

227
00:12:09,305 --> 00:12:10,525
when it comes to bargaining position.

228
00:12:12,160 --> 00:12:15,882
And as we've spoken about at the start,

229
00:12:16,522 --> 00:12:18,263
if the contract has been drafted by the publisher,

230
00:12:18,643 --> 00:12:20,705
you can bet that in the event of the dispute,

231
00:12:20,785 --> 00:12:22,005
the publisher is going to come out on top.

232
00:12:26,168 --> 00:12:27,668
So what does an assignment clause look like?

233
00:12:28,909 --> 00:12:29,970
In fact, something like this.

234
00:12:31,831 --> 00:12:34,472
In this case, the developer owns 50% of its game IP

235
00:12:34,973 --> 00:12:37,034
and assigns the other 50% to the publisher.

236
00:12:37,574 --> 00:12:40,516
Thereafter, the game IP is held 50-50 between the parties.

237
00:12:41,289 --> 00:12:44,190
So if we use the analogy of two people sharing a house,

238
00:12:44,790 --> 00:12:45,891
one person gets the upstairs,

239
00:12:46,211 --> 00:12:47,511
and the other person gets the downstairs.

240
00:12:49,812 --> 00:12:51,272
So how does this work in practice?

241
00:12:51,352 --> 00:12:54,413
Because if the publisher doesn't have all of the game IP,

242
00:12:55,714 --> 00:12:57,914
also they'll likely need an exclusive license

243
00:12:57,934 --> 00:12:59,975
to actually use the developer share of the IP anyway.

244
00:13:00,615 --> 00:13:03,756
So we get to a situation where in order to make this work,

245
00:13:04,317 --> 00:13:06,877
the publisher also needs an exclusive license

246
00:13:06,917 --> 00:13:08,198
in order to use the developer share.

247
00:13:09,947 --> 00:13:11,528
So some common arguments or reasons

248
00:13:12,008 --> 00:13:13,888
suggested by publishers as to why they need

249
00:13:13,908 --> 00:13:15,448
an assignment of your IP.

250
00:13:15,909 --> 00:13:17,809
It might be 50%, it might be more, it might be less.

251
00:13:19,049 --> 00:13:20,170
But the common arguments are,

252
00:13:20,950 --> 00:13:22,850
we need this to protect our investment in you.

253
00:13:24,171 --> 00:13:25,551
This gives us something tangible

254
00:13:25,571 --> 00:13:26,751
that we can show our investors.

255
00:13:28,051 --> 00:13:31,072
Or one more frighteningly that I heard fairly recently was,

256
00:13:31,592 --> 00:13:33,293
we need this in case you go insolvent.

257
00:13:35,193 --> 00:13:37,814
So when might an IP assignment

258
00:13:37,874 --> 00:13:39,194
or partial assignment be justified?

259
00:13:40,622 --> 00:13:43,544
And there's nothing wrong with assigning your rights away in theory,

260
00:13:44,264 --> 00:13:48,888
but if the plan is for the game IP to revert to you at the end of a set period of time,

261
00:13:49,989 --> 00:13:52,951
or when the publisher is in breach, then you need to make sure that that is in the contract.

262
00:13:53,892 --> 00:13:57,154
Otherwise, you might have given your rights to the publisher and you can't get them back.

263
00:14:01,718 --> 00:14:06,561
Whereas the previous example was pretty clear that the developer and publisher would carry the IP 50-50,

264
00:14:07,282 --> 00:14:09,303
you need to be aware of sneaky assignments like this one.

265
00:14:10,558 --> 00:14:12,219
On the face of it, it seems fairly innocuous.

266
00:14:12,239 --> 00:14:15,781
I mean, after all, what's 1% of your game?

267
00:14:16,241 --> 00:14:17,882
What's 1% of the game IP?

268
00:14:18,862 --> 00:14:21,444
However, co-ownership of IP rules

269
00:14:21,824 --> 00:14:23,045
actually give this a lot of power

270
00:14:23,085 --> 00:14:25,126
to the publisher in this case.

271
00:14:25,426 --> 00:14:27,927
So if you're giving any share of your IP away,

272
00:14:28,307 --> 00:14:30,108
you need to make sure that at the end of a contract,

273
00:14:30,389 --> 00:14:31,289
you get the rights back.

274
00:14:31,749 --> 00:14:33,590
And that goes doubly in the event

275
00:14:33,610 --> 00:14:34,811
that the publisher is in breach.

276
00:14:35,151 --> 00:14:36,372
There's no way they should be holding on

277
00:14:36,512 --> 00:14:38,013
to your game IP in that case.

278
00:14:43,073 --> 00:14:48,358
So some quick fixes. If you receive a publishing contract with an IP assignment, ask yourself

279
00:14:48,398 --> 00:14:54,304
the following questions. Am I comfortable with giving away the rights to my game to

280
00:14:54,324 --> 00:14:59,690
my publisher? The answer might be yes. If this is your first game and this deal gives

281
00:14:59,710 --> 00:15:04,434
you sufficient funds to live, pay rent, eat food, all that good stuff, then it might be

282
00:15:04,454 --> 00:15:05,095
the right thing to do.

283
00:15:06,526 --> 00:15:10,007
If the answer's no, then does the contract provide

284
00:15:10,027 --> 00:15:11,308
for the game IP to come back to you

285
00:15:11,348 --> 00:15:12,428
after a certain period of time

286
00:15:13,029 --> 00:15:14,289
or where the publisher is in breach?

287
00:15:16,590 --> 00:15:18,811
If not, then that either needs to be fixed

288
00:15:18,971 --> 00:15:20,892
or you need to make sure that you're fairly compensated

289
00:15:21,132 --> 00:15:22,853
for the fact that you're effectively going to be selling

290
00:15:22,873 --> 00:15:26,614
your IP to the publisher.

291
00:15:26,714 --> 00:15:28,295
Understand the reasons why a publisher

292
00:15:28,315 --> 00:15:30,996
would want to take ownership or part ownership of your IP

293
00:15:31,476 --> 00:15:32,957
and ask why they can't get the same result

294
00:15:32,977 --> 00:15:34,277
from having an exclusive license.

295
00:15:36,476 --> 00:15:41,478
You also need to make sure there's a carve out for your proprietary tools, tech, and code libraries.

296
00:15:42,778 --> 00:15:45,900
These might be things that you want to use from project to project,

297
00:15:45,960 --> 00:15:48,220
or you might have already used in previous games that you've made.

298
00:15:49,061 --> 00:15:51,842
An assignment of IP can be pretty much a blunt instrument.

299
00:15:51,862 --> 00:15:54,863
So if you're assigning all the intellectual property rights in a game,

300
00:15:55,363 --> 00:15:58,745
that will also include things that you necessarily might want to use again.

301
00:15:59,245 --> 00:16:03,826
So you need to carve those out and provide the publisher with a non-exclusive license to use those.

302
00:16:05,048 --> 00:16:08,432
That will allow you to use those again for your future projects.

303
00:16:13,677 --> 00:16:16,340
Exclusive licenses are far more common than IP assignments

304
00:16:16,440 --> 00:16:18,241
in terms of how a publisher gets the permission

305
00:16:18,522 --> 00:16:19,563
from you to publish your game.

306
00:16:21,104 --> 00:16:23,887
This license will normally give the publisher sole permission

307
00:16:23,927 --> 00:16:26,029
to publish, distribute, and otherwise exploit

308
00:16:26,069 --> 00:16:28,872
the game across various platforms and countries

309
00:16:28,892 --> 00:16:29,853
for a set period of time.

310
00:16:31,765 --> 00:16:36,308
In granting this permission, you're also going to exclude yourself as the developer from being able to sell the game during this time.

311
00:16:38,289 --> 00:16:47,755
However, if it's done wrong, an exclusive license can also be equivalent to an IP assignment or an IP transfer, and you can easily lock up your rights with the publisher if you're not careful.

312
00:16:49,116 --> 00:16:52,479
So an example of a publishing license looks like this.

313
00:16:58,543 --> 00:16:59,583
As you can see in this slide here.

314
