sorry, previous slide, as you can see here,

315
00:17:04,020 --> 00:17:05,321
you can see it gives exclusive right

316
00:17:05,401 --> 00:17:06,902
during the term and throughout the territory

317
00:17:07,283 --> 00:17:08,784
to be able to publish and otherwise export the game

318
00:17:08,804 --> 00:17:09,425
on the platforms.

319
00:17:14,729 --> 00:17:16,090
So as you can see from that example,

320
00:17:16,110 --> 00:17:18,372
a publishing license is normally limited

321
00:17:18,392 --> 00:17:19,533
in the following ways.

322
00:17:20,634 --> 00:17:22,416
Term, that being the length of time

323
00:17:22,456 --> 00:17:24,598
during which the publisher can promote and sell the game,

324
00:17:25,439 --> 00:17:27,821
this would normally be somewhere between five and 10 years.

325
00:17:29,124 --> 00:17:33,646
The territories, that being the countries around the world where the publisher can promote and sell your game.

326
00:17:34,987 --> 00:17:42,691
And the platforms, the formats or distribution channels where the publisher can sell your game, such as Steam, Nintendo Switch, Playstation, Xbox, that kind of stuff.

327
00:17:43,852 --> 00:17:50,756
So this brings us to our second contract killer, Bad License Terms, where we're going to look at these publishing licenses in a bit more detail.

328
00:17:54,753 --> 00:17:58,055
So we'll start off by looking at the first two areas that will be caught by a publishing licence

329
00:17:58,635 --> 00:18:01,157
They're the term of the agreement and the territories caught by it

330
00:18:07,661 --> 00:18:11,004
So here's an example of a pretty standard definition of a publishing licence term

331
00:18:11,444 --> 00:18:13,385
describing how long the publishing licence will last for

332
00:18:14,606 --> 00:18:18,769
So as you can see it says five years and that's nice within the standard range we're most likely to see

333
00:18:19,789 --> 00:18:22,171
But be aware of the second part that's highlighted in red here

334
00:18:23,677 --> 00:18:26,338
it's actually five years from the last version of the game that's released.

335
00:18:27,099 --> 00:18:32,863
So if the definition of game includes any DLC, add-ons, or maybe even ports

336
00:18:32,923 --> 00:18:36,986
or different versions of the game, then the five years will be reset every

337
00:18:37,006 --> 00:18:38,467
time a new version is released.

338
00:18:38,907 --> 00:18:40,488
So you need to be aware of that.

339
00:18:41,129 --> 00:18:43,430
So check the publishing term quite carefully.

340
00:18:47,793 --> 00:18:50,856
As we mentioned earlier, the exclusive part of a license is the permission

341
00:18:50,896 --> 00:18:52,517
given to the publisher to do certain things.

342
00:18:53,666 --> 00:18:56,628
to the exclusion of anyone else, and that includes you as the developer.

343
00:18:58,028 --> 00:19:00,890
So normally these publishing licenses are granted for a set period of time,

344
00:19:02,111 --> 00:19:06,273
that being a fair amount of time for the publisher to have a fair crack at publishing your game,

345
00:19:06,873 --> 00:19:10,015
normally between 5 and 10 years, but they vary from publisher to publisher.

346
00:19:11,596 --> 00:19:17,659
So you need to be aware of long license periods. For example, if a publisher's license is lasting

347
00:19:17,699 --> 00:19:20,380
for 25 years, like in the bottom example here.

348
00:19:22,799 --> 00:19:26,483
Or you need to be careful where a publisher takes the rights to your game in perpetuity.

349
00:19:27,144 --> 00:19:28,085
Like the top example.

350
00:19:28,926 --> 00:19:31,428
That's obviously perpetuity meaning forever.

351
00:19:32,449 --> 00:19:36,874
In that case, you need to be prepared not to get your rights to your game back.

352
00:19:37,635 --> 00:19:40,238
And that's even where the publisher's not doing a good job.

353
00:19:41,119 --> 00:19:42,260
So, how do you fix it?

354
00:19:43,158 --> 00:19:47,001
Well, simple answer, ask for a shorter license period.

355
00:19:47,742 --> 00:19:51,025
The publisher needs a reasonable amount of time to publish the game and that's it.

356
00:19:51,345 --> 00:19:57,430
If they need anything longer, then ask why and try and get an understanding of how they plan to use your rights going forward.

357
00:19:58,191 --> 00:20:02,635
You don't really want their rights just sitting on the shelf or them not distributing your game after 10 years time.

358
00:20:03,135 --> 00:20:06,518
After that time, you probably want those rights back so you can do something with them yourself.

359
00:20:11,390 --> 00:20:15,271
And even shorter licences might be able to run on beyond the initial agreed term.

360
00:20:16,212 --> 00:20:18,272
And that might happen through an auto renewal mechanism.

361
00:20:19,653 --> 00:20:21,894
This might work through inaction by either side.

362
00:20:22,054 --> 00:20:25,875
So for example, the licence term we saw on the previous page of five years, it

363
00:20:25,895 --> 00:20:31,237
might just renew for an additional period of one year, and that might be if no one

364
00:20:31,277 --> 00:20:35,519
has given notice to terminate before the end of that five years, the contract will

365
00:20:35,539 --> 00:20:38,700
just renew either for another year, might be two years, might be another five years.

366
00:20:39,973 --> 00:20:42,955
So it's sort of like your PS Plus or your Amazon subscription.

367
00:20:43,516 --> 00:20:47,379
If you don't terminate in time before it renews again, effectively,

368
00:20:47,660 --> 00:20:50,602
you have to pay again and you're locked in for another year.

369
00:20:51,703 --> 00:20:55,066
So how to fix this, you need to know how long the license term runs for

370
00:20:56,027 --> 00:20:58,469
and how much notice you need to give before the end of the initial term

371
00:20:58,930 --> 00:21:01,172
in order to get out of it, if that's what you want to do.

372
00:21:03,053 --> 00:21:07,317
Another example of an auto-renewal might be like the example here.

373
00:21:08,532 --> 00:21:12,494
Here the contract extends for one year terms, where the game is still generating revenues

374
00:21:12,534 --> 00:21:13,574
above a certain threshold.

375
00:21:14,295 --> 00:21:18,377
And that enables the publisher to continue benefiting from selling the game, even though

376
00:21:18,397 --> 00:21:19,457
the initial term has ended.

377
00:21:20,238 --> 00:21:25,821
And it's how you'd expect those smash hit games to still be, or how a publisher can

378
00:21:25,841 --> 00:21:30,243
make sure that an evergreen game or game that's an absolute smash hit, how they can ensure

379
00:21:30,283 --> 00:21:33,445
that they can keep publishing it, even long after the initial term might have ended.

380
00:21:35,059 --> 00:21:45,126
In theory, this might be a nice compromise, since the game itself that you've created and the publisher's marketing actions should have helped generate revenues long after the game has been released.

381
00:21:46,767 --> 00:21:56,394
However, you need to be aware of setting the threshold too low. Like the example shown here, â‚¬10,000 might be too low a bar to set when taking into account the publisher's cut.

382
00:21:57,494 --> 00:22:03,158
In this case, it might be better for the developer to self-publish their own game at this point, so you might want to ask for the rights back.

383
00:22:10,139 --> 00:22:12,240
Let's look at how far a publishing license can reach.

384
00:22:13,961 --> 00:22:15,621
Most publishers will ask for worldwide rights

385
00:22:15,661 --> 00:22:16,381
to publish your game.

386
00:22:16,902 --> 00:22:19,063
That's so they can sell it in as many countries as possible.

387
00:22:20,263 --> 00:22:22,304
So you normally need to check the definition of territory

388
00:22:22,704 --> 00:22:24,385
in the agreement to see exactly what this is

389
00:22:24,405 --> 00:22:25,485
and exactly what they're taking.

390
00:22:27,246 --> 00:22:29,126
And this is a genuine example of a publishing country

391
00:22:29,146 --> 00:22:31,607
that I've seen recently, how they define territory.

392
00:22:32,828 --> 00:22:34,508
And I just quite like the ambition that they show here,

393
00:22:34,548 --> 00:22:35,489
that they might need the rights

394
00:22:35,949 --> 00:22:37,490
to cover parts of space in the future.

395
00:22:40,045 --> 00:22:44,448
And there's nothing wrong with a publisher wanting to publish the game in as many countries or planets as possible.

396
00:22:46,350 --> 00:22:50,453
As a developer, you want the game to get in the hands of as many players as possible around the globe.

397
00:22:51,374 --> 00:22:56,278
However, you should ask the publisher how they plan, what is in their marketing plan,

398
00:22:56,778 --> 00:23:00,581
and to confirm where they plan on selling the game and how they're going to do it.

399
00:23:01,782 --> 00:23:06,006
It is unlikely that the publisher has a presence in every territory around the globe.

400
00:23:06,486 --> 00:23:09,348
So they're going to be using third parties in different territories to help them do it.

401
00:23:10,636 --> 00:23:14,079
So you should know how they plan to do this and who they plan to use.

402
00:23:15,220 --> 00:23:18,243
If possible, ask for case studies based on the developers in their portfolio.

403
00:23:20,305 --> 00:23:22,707
If they don't have plans to publish your game in any of the territories,

404
00:23:22,727 --> 00:23:26,451
for example, China, then you don't necessarily need to give those rights away.

405
00:23:26,471 --> 00:23:29,473
It's better you find another partner for those rights.

406
00:23:30,234 --> 00:23:32,536
That might be a different publisher or might be doing it yourself,

407
00:23:32,556 --> 00:23:36,180
rather than have those rights waste away on the publisher's shelf.

408
00:23:48,200 --> 00:23:49,381
So contract killer number three.

409
00:23:50,822 --> 00:23:52,244
Still looking at bad license terms,

410
00:23:52,404 --> 00:23:54,526
but this time we'll look at the platforms and porting.

411
00:23:56,128 --> 00:23:57,369
So as we've seen with term and territory,

412
00:23:57,389 --> 00:23:58,610
the publisher is going to want to take rights

413
00:23:58,650 --> 00:24:00,051
on as many platforms as possible.

414
00:24:00,932 --> 00:24:02,554
They'll want the license to be as long as possible

415
00:24:03,775 --> 00:24:05,477
and to cover as many countries as possible too.

416
00:24:10,862 --> 00:24:12,043
As you can see from this example.

417
00:24:13,712 --> 00:24:16,373
the publisher is asking for rights to pretty much all platforms.

418
00:24:17,113 --> 00:24:20,215
And that also includes a catch-all so that they can put the game out on any

419
00:24:20,275 --> 00:24:22,636
next generation platforms that arise in the next 10 years.

420
00:24:23,776 --> 00:24:25,317
So yeah, it's pretty broad.

421
00:24:28,438 --> 00:24:31,660
The rationale that publishers will give for this is that they want to control

422
00:24:31,700 --> 00:24:36,842
the marketing across all territories and platforms and thereby control the quality.

423
00:24:50,019 --> 00:24:52,780
However, if the publisher is taking rights for all platforms,

424
00:24:54,041 --> 00:24:57,243
you should check whether you have to deliver a version of the game for all of the platforms too.

425
00:24:59,024 --> 00:25:01,145
So first off, check what are you being paid to develop.

426
00:25:02,405 --> 00:25:04,346
If you're only developing the Steam version of the game,

427
00:25:05,106 --> 00:25:07,628
and that's the only version you're going to deliver to the publisher,

428
00:25:08,208 --> 00:25:09,709
then you need to include that in the contract.

429
00:25:10,429 --> 00:25:12,890
Otherwise, you might be on the hook to develop console versions as well.

430
00:25:15,345 --> 00:25:18,226
A key thing to check might be including PC versions.

431
00:25:18,707 --> 00:25:20,767
PC might also include Windows,

432
00:25:20,927 --> 00:25:24,049
but it might also include Linux and macOS.

433
00:25:24,709 --> 00:25:26,830
If you don't have the ability to develop for Linux and macOS,

434
00:25:26,850 --> 00:25:27,910
then you might want to exclude that.

435
00:25:28,270 --> 00:25:29,951
And you might want to specify that PC means

436
00:25:30,151 --> 00:25:31,111
Windows PC only.

437
00:25:34,232 --> 00:25:35,753
If the contract is clear as to what platforms

438
00:25:35,773 --> 00:25:36,373
you're delivering,

439
00:25:37,174 --> 00:25:38,654
then you should ask who's going to be developing

440
00:25:38,694 --> 00:25:39,775
the other platform versions.

441
00:25:40,949 --> 00:25:45,550
If they don't have plans to develop these right now, then ask why they need the rights right now.

442
00:25:46,951 --> 00:25:51,072
If the publisher is only providing refunding for the Steam or PC version, as we mentioned,

443
00:25:51,512 --> 00:25:57,253
then you shouldn't necessarily have to lock up the rights for console, mobile, or other non-funded platforms with that publisher,

444
00:25:58,273 --> 00:26:03,395
unless they've shown you that they do have specific plans to create versions for those games and those platforms,

445
00:26:03,955 --> 00:26:05,575
and that they're going to cover the cost of doing so.

446
00:26:08,130 --> 00:26:10,071
Rather than locking up those rights to the start,

447
00:26:10,511 --> 00:26:12,792
a more developer-friendly approach

448
00:26:13,492 --> 00:26:15,253
might be to give the publisher a first option

449
00:26:15,573 --> 00:26:17,834
to publish on those platforms or to fund the publishing

450
00:26:18,214 --> 00:26:19,855
and fund the development and publishing

451
00:26:20,015 --> 00:26:22,356
of those ports or console versions.

452
00:26:24,317 --> 00:26:26,638
That means they don't get the rights initially to make them,

453
00:26:26,718 --> 00:26:29,499
but they get first dibs in case they want to fund them

454
00:26:29,559 --> 00:26:30,739
or develop them down the line,

455
00:26:31,139 --> 00:26:33,580
or in the event that you want to find an alternative funder

456
00:26:34,041 --> 00:26:36,422
or third-party partner to fund and develop them.

457
00:26:38,952 --> 00:26:41,213
So that's a fair and reasonable approach for both sides,

458
00:26:41,233 --> 00:26:42,733
since the publisher gets a fair chance

459
00:26:42,793 --> 00:26:44,234
to fund those ports at a later date,

460
00:26:45,175 --> 00:26:47,056
presumably once they've seen how well the game is sold

461
00:26:47,116 --> 00:26:48,996
on the initial platform that they're funding you.

462
00:26:49,697 --> 00:26:51,258
But it also allows you as the developer

463
00:26:51,278 --> 00:26:52,798
to explore other options in the event

464
00:26:52,818 --> 00:26:55,960
that the publisher doesn't actually pick that option up

465
00:26:56,100 --> 00:26:57,501
and they aren't interested in publishing the game

466
00:26:57,541 --> 00:26:58,241
on those consoles.

467
00:27:03,464 --> 00:27:05,445
If it's agreed that the game will be ported,

468
00:27:05,645 --> 00:27:06,865
then check who's doing the porting.

469
00:27:08,098 --> 00:27:11,179
Do you have the in-house expertise to develop the console versions?

470
00:27:12,600 --> 00:27:15,721
If so, then you might want the first option to develop them and be paid for

471
00:27:15,761 --> 00:27:19,682
doing so rather than the publisher doing this in-house or engaging another third

472
00:27:19,702 --> 00:27:21,183
party to do that development.

473
00:27:23,284 --> 00:27:26,845
If you don't have those expertise, then the publisher might develop these in-house

474
00:27:26,905 --> 00:27:32,427
or they might engage a third party, but check the contract to make sure that it

475
00:27:32,467 --> 00:27:35,468
provides something about the quality of the development of those ports.

476
00:27:37,129 --> 00:27:41,573
As the developer you're going to be providing various warranties and representations and legal promises

477
00:27:42,113 --> 00:27:44,955
about the quality of the game that you're delivering to the publisher.

478
00:27:46,757 --> 00:27:51,560
So if the publisher or its third party partner is going to be porting the game

479
00:27:52,001 --> 00:27:55,623
they should be providing those same legal promises to you about the quality of the ports.

