00:32:31,680 --> 00:32:36,841
That is in your interest too, but if the restrictions are too broad then you should ask them to be changed.

557
00:32:39,982 --> 00:32:42,364
Check what the publishing license also actually attaches to.

558
00:32:42,564 --> 00:32:46,468
Does it include other rights like merchandise, the soundtrack, or film TV rights?

559
00:32:47,468 --> 00:32:50,671
In some cases, the definition of game might also refer to merchandise,

560
00:32:51,312 --> 00:32:53,454
or ancillary products, or something similar.

561
00:32:55,296 --> 00:32:58,138
These might be subject to the same exclusive publishing license.

562
00:32:58,619 --> 00:33:01,762
And as we've drilled to death already in this talk,

563
00:33:01,902 --> 00:33:04,324
exclusive also means that you can't do anything with them.

564
00:33:07,356 --> 00:33:11,040
In some cases you might be fine with these rights being in the publisher's hands

565
00:33:11,981 --> 00:33:14,543
however in each case you should know what the publisher plans to do with it

566
00:33:15,084 --> 00:33:17,126
and do they actually have any plans to use them.

567
00:33:18,667 --> 00:33:21,590
Also if you've already signed deals, merch deals with companies

568
00:33:21,950 --> 00:33:23,212
prior to signing with the publisher

569
00:33:24,493 --> 00:33:27,215
then your exclusive licence with the publisher might also cut across that

570
00:33:28,417 --> 00:33:32,100
and it might put you in breach of the other deals you might have already signed.

571
00:33:34,339 --> 00:33:44,496
So you might need to carve those out or carve it out with the publisher or just give the publisher non-exclusive rights so that you haven't harmed their rights, they still have some rights to use it.

572
00:33:44,876 --> 00:33:47,561
But you make sure you're under breach of any other contracts you've signed.

573
00:33:49,692 --> 00:33:55,098
Another option that we often see now is that, especially indie developers, might grant rights

574
00:33:55,198 --> 00:34:01,224
to the composer of the game's soundtrack so that they can release the game or benefit

575
00:34:01,244 --> 00:34:05,589
from a revenue share from sales of the game's soundtrack, or allow the composer to sell

576
00:34:05,629 --> 00:34:09,673
the game's soundtrack or distribute it via their own channels, whether that's on Spotify,

577
00:34:09,713 --> 00:34:11,735
Bandcamp, Soundcloud, or something similar.

578
00:34:13,250 --> 00:34:16,853
So if you do have those terms already agreed, then you again, you need to make sure that

579
00:34:16,893 --> 00:34:18,494
you don't cut across them with the publisher.

580
00:34:18,815 --> 00:34:20,176
Just make sure that the publisher is aware.

581
00:34:20,937 --> 00:34:24,600
It's highly likely that you can come to some arrangement whereby both sides are happy.

582
00:34:27,122 --> 00:34:30,685
And also check whether the scope of ancillary products includes film and TV rights.

583
00:34:31,390 --> 00:34:32,291
that relate to the game.

584
00:34:33,131 --> 00:34:34,932
Does the publisher have any plans to use these?

585
00:34:35,613 --> 00:34:37,414
If not, then just ask to remove them.

586
00:34:38,254 --> 00:34:40,796
The publisher can also always ask for a right

587
00:34:40,836 --> 00:34:42,577
of first refusal like we just talked about.

588
00:34:42,657 --> 00:34:44,358
So if you do plan to use them in the future,

589
00:34:44,818 --> 00:34:46,139
or if they want to use them in the future,

590
00:34:46,159 --> 00:34:47,320
they can always come back and ask,

591
00:34:47,400 --> 00:34:48,781
and you come back and negotiate for them.

592
00:34:54,264 --> 00:34:56,465
So now that we've looked at bad license terms,

593
00:34:56,925 --> 00:34:58,946
let's turn our attention to how you actually get paid.

594
00:35:00,328 --> 00:35:02,148
So the primary reason for most developers

595
00:35:02,168 --> 00:35:04,309
wanting publisher support is access to funding.

596
00:35:05,030 --> 00:35:06,450
That might be cash during development

597
00:35:06,590 --> 00:35:08,091
so that you can actually help finish your game

598
00:35:08,911 --> 00:35:10,411
or so, you know, helps pay the rent,

599
00:35:10,832 --> 00:35:12,412
helps you eat and live.

600
00:35:14,553 --> 00:35:16,514
And we'll refer to these development payments

601
00:35:16,534 --> 00:35:18,534
that you receive prior to the launch of your game

602
00:35:18,634 --> 00:35:19,535
as front-end payments.

603
00:35:20,575 --> 00:35:23,376
But obviously publishers also have a great marketing reach.

604
00:35:23,396 --> 00:35:24,677
So they might also be providing

605
00:35:24,717 --> 00:35:26,317
with revenue payments as well.

606
00:35:26,817 --> 00:35:27,418
That being...

607
00:35:28,444 --> 00:35:33,726
revenues generated from the sales of your game and we'll call these back-end payments. So for

608
00:35:33,746 --> 00:35:39,229
this section we'll look at those bad payment terms that might affect how you get paid during development.

609
00:35:42,571 --> 00:35:47,574
So what are front-end payments? So as I've just alluded to, these front-end payments are made by

610
00:35:47,594 --> 00:35:52,517
a publisher to you during development. They usually come in the form of development fees, development

611
00:35:52,577 --> 00:35:57,560
advances, but you might also see them referred to as guarantees or MG, something like that.

612
00:35:58,556 --> 00:36:00,978
So for simplicity, I'm just going to refer to them as front-end payments.

613
00:36:01,478 --> 00:36:04,081
That being fees you received prior to the release of your game.

614
00:36:06,042 --> 00:36:07,924
Now, it's unusual for a publisher just

615
00:36:07,944 --> 00:36:11,307
to hand over cash to you without any sort of control in place.

616
00:36:12,187 --> 00:36:15,230
So as such, front-end payments are going to be tied to a couple of things.

617
00:36:15,890 --> 00:36:19,974
That will be your obligation to develop and deliver certain builds or milestones.

618
00:36:21,499 --> 00:36:27,487
and they will almost certainly be tied to the publisher's approval of those builds or milestones that you've delivered.

619
00:36:28,087 --> 00:36:36,258
So you're only going to receive a front-end payment in respect of that build and milestone once you've actually delivered it and once the publisher has signed off on it.

620
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:39,623
So how is this dealt with in the contract?

621
00:36:40,889 --> 00:36:42,990
So most publishing contracts will have terms

622
00:36:43,470 --> 00:36:46,172
outlining the delivery evaluation feedback mechanism

623
00:36:46,392 --> 00:36:47,032
and requirements.

624
00:36:47,532 --> 00:36:50,494
For example, your delivery of a particular milestone

625
00:36:50,914 --> 00:36:53,095
or build is going to be tied to dates in the contract,

626
00:36:53,515 --> 00:36:57,257
most likely linked or listed in a milestone schedule

627
00:36:57,597 --> 00:36:59,158
or delivery schedule or something similar.

628
00:37:00,819 --> 00:37:02,299
There should then be a mechanic

629
00:37:02,659 --> 00:37:03,740
that provides for the publisher

630
00:37:03,780 --> 00:37:05,141
to review that milestone or build.

631
00:37:05,961 --> 00:37:07,222
And they'll either approve it

632
00:37:07,382 --> 00:37:08,382
and that will trigger payment.

633
00:37:09,086 --> 00:37:13,427
or they reject it, whereupon the developer, you will have to implement fixes

634
00:37:13,747 --> 00:37:17,929
and then resubmit the build to the publisher, whereupon that whole process begins again.

635
00:37:20,129 --> 00:37:22,710
But what happens if you don't get publisher approval?

636
00:37:25,051 --> 00:37:29,472
Well, there might be valid reasons why a publisher has rejected a milestone. For example, it doesn't

637
00:37:29,512 --> 00:37:33,554
comply with the agreed specification or the build requirements that have been set out in the

638
00:37:33,594 --> 00:37:38,275
milestone schedule. However, what if issues are there that aren't your fault?

639
00:37:39,427 --> 00:37:45,173
An absolute publishing agreement classic is not accounting for delays that are caused by the publisher.

640
00:37:46,835 --> 00:37:56,545
And that would be, or can be caused, especially where there's no timing specified for the publisher to perform certain actions, such as reviewing the bill that you've just delivered.

641
00:37:58,126 --> 00:38:01,868
This can be a major issue, especially if the publisher's

642
00:38:01,908 --> 00:38:03,489
delay in carrying out their obligations

643
00:38:03,949 --> 00:38:05,831
is going to affect your ability to get paid.

644
00:38:05,851 --> 00:38:09,293
It's also grossly unfair, because you can see the knock-on effect.

645
00:38:09,853 --> 00:38:10,834
You deliver a build.

646
00:38:10,934 --> 00:38:13,335
You're waiting for the publisher to sign off on it.

647
00:38:13,375 --> 00:38:14,175
They don't sign off.

648
00:38:14,716 --> 00:38:15,576
You don't get the money.

649
00:38:16,177 --> 00:38:18,198
You then can't finish the next build,

650
00:38:18,358 --> 00:38:20,419
because you haven't had the money to develop it.

651
00:38:21,000 --> 00:38:22,981
And then you're in breach of the contract for not

652
00:38:23,021 --> 00:38:24,061
delivering that next build.

653
00:38:24,922 --> 00:38:29,424
So again, that's going to then put you in breach of contract and it's not your fault.

654
00:38:29,784 --> 00:38:35,867
And how is that fair? So how can this be solved? So to avoid delays that aren't your fault,

655
00:38:36,507 --> 00:38:40,548
you can put time limits on the publisher to perform certain tasks. In particular,

656
00:38:40,588 --> 00:38:43,790
there are obligations around evaluation and approval of builds and milestones.

657
00:38:44,550 --> 00:38:50,032
This is completely normal practice and publishers are generally amenable to having a reasonable

658
00:38:50,072 --> 00:38:51,573
amount of time to review each milestone.

659
00:38:53,110 --> 00:38:54,651
normally 10 working days.

660
00:38:57,252 --> 00:38:59,434
But if a mechanism like this isn't in the contract,

661
00:38:59,454 --> 00:39:00,554
then be sure to add it in.

662
00:39:04,076 --> 00:39:06,457
But what happens if you still haven't received a response

663
00:39:06,518 --> 00:39:07,758
after that time limit is up?

664
00:39:09,019 --> 00:39:11,320
Well, it's also common practice for a developer

665
00:39:11,360 --> 00:39:13,161
to ask for automatic approval

666
00:39:13,201 --> 00:39:15,883
if the developer hasn't given his approval or rejection

667
00:39:15,923 --> 00:39:17,103
within the agreed time limit.

668
00:39:18,367 --> 00:39:29,090
That will be approval for the purposes of payment only, I might add, but it's usually a fair compromise because it means that you can get paid and you can invoice for the next milestone and start working on that.

669
00:39:29,670 --> 00:39:38,773
But it also allows the publisher for you to also allows the publisher to ask you to make changes or fixes to that build in the event that it's broken all those bugs that need fixing.

670
00:39:44,098 --> 00:39:49,762
Publishers should also not be rejecting milestones or builds that meet the agreed specification or delivery schedule.

671
00:39:50,303 --> 00:39:52,665
That is, they shouldn't just be arbitrarily rejecting builds.

672
00:39:53,746 --> 00:40:01,211
So if it isn't already included in your contract, then you need to be sure to add in a requirement on them to provide reasonably detailed feedback where there is any rejection.

673
00:40:02,693 --> 00:40:07,436
The whole point of the evaluation and review process is so that the development of the game stays on track.

674
00:40:08,797 --> 00:40:12,160
And the publisher will guide that development in the event that it goes off course.

675
00:40:13,967 --> 00:40:15,748
So any feedback or rejection that they give

676
00:40:16,989 --> 00:40:18,751
needs to be sufficient or should be sufficient

677
00:40:19,632 --> 00:40:21,974
for you to be able to make the necessary changes to the build

678
00:40:23,415 --> 00:40:26,538
in order for it to comply with the agreed specification delivery schedule.

679
00:40:29,221 --> 00:40:32,444
The publisher shouldn't also change the agreed scope or specification

680
00:40:33,465 --> 00:40:35,387
of any deliverables once that's been fixed.

681
00:40:36,948 --> 00:40:37,048
So...

682
00:40:38,192 --> 00:40:44,376
It's good practice for the parties to agree the specification and milestone deliverables at the start before anything happens.

683
00:40:46,177 --> 00:40:52,842
You might also have a more agile process whereby the next builders agree between the parties once you've delivered the next milestone.

684
00:40:53,422 --> 00:40:58,205
That's also fine, but make sure that the negotiation process is fair and they are adding any

685
00:40:59,347 --> 00:41:04,913
and they aren't adding any unreasonable features that require more time, money or resources for you to actually implement

686
00:41:05,573 --> 00:41:10,058
so check if you've got the creative control and vision of the game that you have control over that

687
00:41:13,883 --> 00:41:17,326
if a publisher wants to make changes to the agreed specification or delivery schedule

688
00:41:17,867 --> 00:41:19,969
then this should naturally require your approval

689
00:41:21,085 --> 00:41:25,248
As of all of them, any changes that require more time, money or resource,

690
00:41:25,268 --> 00:41:28,410
that being, you need to bring more people onto the project to help,

691
00:41:29,031 --> 00:41:31,252
should be seen as outside of the agreed specification.

692
00:41:32,613 --> 00:41:34,835
That's not to say you and the publisher can't agree those changes

693
00:41:34,855 --> 00:41:35,856
at a later date if you want,

694
00:41:36,576 --> 00:41:39,779
but you should be ensured that you're paid for any extra work or deliverables.

695
00:41:40,539 --> 00:41:42,821
And that would normally require an amendment to the contract

696
00:41:43,181 --> 00:41:46,224
to adjust the agreed spec and reflect the fact

697
00:41:46,244 --> 00:41:48,025
that you're going to get paid a bit more in order to do it.

698
00:41:50,292 --> 00:41:55,498
To avoid this scope creep, you want to make sure that the contract should include a change mechanism in order to avoid that.

699
00:41:56,259 --> 00:42:03,266
And that scope creep term is normally associated with freelance or work-for-hire arrangements, but it can also play a part in publishing agreements too.

700
00:42:07,831 --> 00:42:11,375
And you need to check the timings in cash flow and how long it is going to take you to get paid.

701
00:42:12,675 --> 00:42:18,098
One of the final points of this section is to understand how long it takes for the publisher

702
00:42:18,118 --> 00:42:22,721
to actually send you the money, and then how long it's actually going to be until it hits

703
00:42:22,741 --> 00:42:23,401
your bank account.

704
00:42:24,522 --> 00:42:26,543
So always check the payment terms of any contract.

705
00:42:27,624 --> 00:42:30,606
The payment terms are the length of time that the publisher takes to make a payment.

706
00:42:31,366 --> 00:42:35,089
In particular, you need to make sure that this doesn't leave you in a bad cash flow

707
00:42:35,129 --> 00:42:35,469
position.

708
00:42:37,154 --> 00:42:41,335
An example of a standard payment term might be 30 days from publishers approval of a milestone.

709
00:42:42,076 --> 00:42:46,257
So that means once the milestone has been approved, then you still have to wait 30 days

710
00:42:46,277 --> 00:42:47,517
for the money to hit your bank account.

711
00:42:48,818 --> 00:42:52,099
If we take a step back as well, and if you factor in the fact that a publisher might

712
00:42:52,119 --> 00:42:56,240
have 10 working days to approve a milestone or review a milestone, then there might be

713
00:42:56,280 --> 00:43:01,162
additional time added on until you actually get the money from the publisher, especially

714
00:43:01,202 --> 00:43:02,942
if there's been a round of reviews or fixes.

715
00:43:03,503 --> 00:43:06,003
So make sure that this doesn't leave you in a bad cash flow position.

716
00:43:07,535 --> 00:43:10,738
If the publisher's payment terms are too long, then ask if they'll change them.

717
00:43:11,599 --> 00:43:15,543
You shouldn't put yourself in a bad financial position, and most publishers are happy to

718
00:43:15,583 --> 00:43:19,807
move milestones around to make sure that you aren't left in the lurch, and make sure you

719
00:43:19,847 --> 00:43:21,569
do have money to live while you're making the game.

720
00:43:25,192 --> 00:43:25,913
So contract killer number 6.

721
00:43:25,953 --> 00:43:29,456
So we're still looking at bad payment terms, but this time on the back end.

722
00:43:30,297 --> 00:43:32,780
That being money that the publisher pays to you once the game is released.

723
00:43:34,245 --> 00:43:37,347
So backend payments are usually in the form of a revenue share,

724
00:43:37,547 --> 00:43:40,389
but you might also see it called royalties, profit share,

725
00:43:40,949 --> 00:43:43,871
or distributed earnings, or something similar like that.

726
00:43:44,672 --> 00:43:46,333
Essentially, it's a percentage of the revenues

727
00:43:46,353 --> 00:43:48,294
that the publisher has received from selling your game.

728
00:43:56,459 --> 00:43:57,879
But backend payments should factor in.

729
00:43:59,017 --> 00:44:03,540
any money that the publisher has received in respect of or revenues attributed to your game.

730
00:44:03,660 --> 00:44:09,384
So not just sales of the game itself, especially if the publishing license includes more than just

731
00:44:09,424 --> 00:44:14,368
game sales, it should include money that the publisher has received from other sources as well

732
00:44:14,908 --> 00:44:18,491
such as cash from exclusivity deals. So for example if they've signed a deal with

733
00:44:19,051 --> 00:44:22,573
for the Epic Game Store or Xbox Game Pass for example.

734
00:44:24,283 --> 00:44:30,610
If your game includes this functionality, then it should also include in-game purchases or in-game advertising.

735
00:44:32,832 --> 00:44:39,239
If merchandise is caught by the publishing license, then you'd also expect revenues from merch sales to be included in this definition too.

736
00:44:40,100 --> 00:44:45,345
And don't forget, if they've got the film and TV rights, you should make sure that you're paid if they ever use them or utilize them.

737
00:44:48,455 --> 00:44:52,159
The back-end payment is going to come to you after the publisher has made certain deductions.

738
00:44:52,839 --> 00:44:57,383
So it's unlikely to be a percentage based on the gross revenues that the game has generated,

739
00:44:58,004 --> 00:45:03,909
that being the total amount of money based on number of sales multiplied by the actual sale price of the game.

740
00:45:05,230 --> 00:45:10,275
Far more likely is that any back-end revenue share is going to be calculated as a percentage of net revenues.

741
00:45:11,016 --> 00:45:15,380
That's the amount that's left over once the publisher has made certain deductions from gross revenue.

742
00:45:17,180 --> 00:45:20,645
So how much does your publisher cost and what deductions are they making?

743
00:45:22,127 --> 00:45:25,532
Publishers are not doing business with you for free and like most businesses,

744
00:45:25,692 --> 00:45:29,177
they will want to make a profit and a publishing agreement gives you an

745
00:45:29,197 --> 00:45:31,701
indication of how they're going to make that profit from you and your game.

746
00:45:33,248 --> 00:45:35,270
So to guarantee a return on their investment,

747
00:45:36,030 --> 00:45:38,532
most publishers will aim to recover their sunk costs incurred

748
00:45:39,133 --> 00:45:41,755
in publishing a game before paying any back-end payments.

749
00:45:42,616 --> 00:45:44,498
So the amount and timing of back-end payments

750
00:45:44,578 --> 00:45:47,780
is likely to depend on the value of those publishers' costs.

751
00:45:48,781 --> 00:45:49,942
As such, you need to know exactly

752
00:45:49,982 --> 00:45:51,444
what the publisher is going to be charging you

753
00:45:51,744 --> 00:45:53,425
so you can show that they're paying you correctly.

754
00:45:57,129 --> 00:46:04,071
So to do this, you need to check the definition of permitted deductions or net receipts and net revenues to determine what the publisher's costs are.

755
00:46:05,552 --> 00:46:09,973
So publishing contracts will deal with this and the publisher's costs in different ways.

756
00:46:10,834 --> 00:46:18,136
A common example is to have a list of permitted deductions or agreed recoupable costs that the publisher can deduct from gross sales revenue.

757
00:46:19,590 --> 00:46:23,071
An alternative approach is to have a definition of net revenues or net receipts,

758
00:46:24,192 --> 00:46:27,213
that being the amount of money left over once the publisher has deducted its costs.

759
00:46:27,753 --> 00:46:30,754
And in that definition, there should be a list of deductions that they're taking.

760
00:46:32,515 --> 00:46:36,856
In either case, it's not unreasonable for you to ascertain exactly what the publisher's costs are.

761
00:46:37,597 --> 00:46:41,798
And you should be asking for evidence that they've incurred them

762
00:46:41,838 --> 00:46:43,679
and exactly what they've been spending.

763
00:46:46,114 --> 00:46:51,038
If a publisher is providing you with front-end payments or advances, then they'll normally have to recoup those first as well.

764
00:46:52,340 --> 00:46:58,325
Ditto with other publishing costs such as marketing, localization, or QA, depending on what services they're doing for you.

765
00:47:00,086 --> 00:47:10,095
However, if a publisher is looking to recoup any internal costs, particularly relating to marketing, porting, or QA services, then you should query the value of those.

766
00:47:11,352 --> 00:47:17,894
Internal publishing costs can be easily inflated and they might not actually represent good value to you as the developer.

767
00:47:19,254 --> 00:47:26,397
For example, it's reasonable for a developer to ask for a publisher's recoverable marketing costs to be limited to third-party costs only.

768
00:47:27,617 --> 00:47:35,260
That being the cost that the publishers are incurred engaging an external PR or marketing firm to help give the game an extra marketing push before launch.

769
00:47:37,442 --> 00:47:41,805
Publishers should also be able to evidence its incurring of any of these publishing costs.

770
00:47:42,586 --> 00:47:46,710
So ask to see evidence of invoices of third party suppliers so that you can verify that

771
00:47:46,750 --> 00:47:49,672
against the statements or information that the publisher is providing to you.

772
00:47:51,654 --> 00:47:54,717
And as a matter of course, most publishing contracts will include audit provisions

773
00:47:55,297 --> 00:47:58,400
and that will allow you to check the publisher's accounts and sales records

774
00:47:58,420 --> 00:47:59,901
to make sure that you've been paid correctly.

775
00:48:01,191 --> 00:48:03,272
If a term like this isn't included in your contract,

776
00:48:03,652 --> 00:48:04,672
then make sure to add it in.

777
00:48:05,092 --> 00:48:07,793
It is fair and reasonable to make sure that you get paid.

778
00:48:07,953 --> 00:48:09,974
So having an audit provision like this

779
00:48:10,314 --> 00:48:11,214
is seen as customary.

780
00:48:15,756 --> 00:48:16,996
Check your payment terms again.

781
00:48:17,016 --> 00:48:19,457
As with front-end payments,

782
00:48:20,238 --> 00:48:22,138
the publisher will usually set out the timescales

783
00:48:22,178 --> 00:48:23,979
for paying the back-end payments as well.

784
00:48:25,359 --> 00:48:27,500
So again, you need to be sure what these are

785
00:48:27,780 --> 00:48:28,540
and change them if you think

786
00:48:28,580 --> 00:48:29,901
it's gonna cause you cashflow issues.

787
00:48:31,789 --> 00:48:35,771
So in particular, in respect of the timing of back-end payments, you should check the following.

788
00:48:38,854 --> 00:48:41,936
And this might not also be the timing, but also the detail that you're getting as well.

789
00:48:42,436 --> 00:48:45,338
So first off, is the publisher providing you with a royalty statement?

790
00:48:46,754 --> 00:48:50,296
So if they are, it's not unreasonable to ask for them

791
00:48:50,316 --> 00:48:52,318
for you to provide information or a statement

792
00:48:52,338 --> 00:48:55,040
based on revenues on a monthly or quarterly basis.

793
00:48:55,721 --> 00:48:56,922
So they might provide a statement

794
00:48:56,962 --> 00:48:58,323
showing a breakdown of game sales

795
00:48:58,363 --> 00:48:59,884
across platform or territory,

796
00:49:00,385 --> 00:49:02,366
or any other information that you might reasonably ask for.

797
00:49:03,862 --> 00:49:05,603
So if that detail isn't in the contract,

798
00:49:05,623 --> 00:49:07,585
then you can always ask for it to be added in.

799
00:49:08,746 --> 00:49:11,788
And some publishers will have example royalty statements

800
00:49:11,808 --> 00:49:14,511
that they use, and they might provide those to you

801
00:49:14,831 --> 00:49:15,892
before you sign the contract,

802
00:49:15,912 --> 00:49:17,393
so you have an idea of what this looks like.

803
00:49:19,755 --> 00:49:20,936
If you're getting a royalty statement,

804
00:49:20,956 --> 00:49:21,957
then that's all well and good,

805
00:49:22,257 --> 00:49:24,339
but check that the publisher is,

806
00:49:24,740 --> 00:49:26,701
check whether the publisher provides you

807
00:49:26,721 --> 00:49:28,763
with the statement first before it pays you,

808
00:49:28,803 --> 00:49:30,384
or if it pays you at the same time.

809
00:49:31,402 --> 00:49:38,506
Because if they're providing the statement to you first, then that might inadvertently extend the amount of time until you actually receive the money in your bank account.

810
00:49:39,087 --> 00:49:45,231
So check that time period in the contract, and then check how long it takes for them to pay you after you've received that statement.

811
00:49:47,362 --> 00:49:51,225
And then you need to calculate how long it's actually going to take for them to actually receive the cash in your bank.

812
00:49:51,825 --> 00:49:58,010
For example, some publishers' payment terms might be 45 days from the end of the month in which they've received revenues.

813
00:49:58,550 --> 00:50:04,455
So you can imagine if they've received revenues on the first of the month, you aren't going to receive that money until 75 days later.

814
00:50:08,938 --> 00:50:14,282
My final point, and it's a big one, and it concerns where the publisher deducts or recoups its costs from.

815
00:50:15,148 --> 00:50:17,468
And by that I mean, how is the publisher actually

816
00:50:17,488 --> 00:50:18,389
recovering its costs?

817
00:50:20,289 --> 00:50:22,310
The most common approach taken by publishers

818
00:50:22,390 --> 00:50:23,950
is for them to recover their sunk costs 100%

819
00:50:24,690 --> 00:50:25,510
from gross revenues.

820
00:50:26,851 --> 00:50:30,032
So once they've hit that break-even point

821
00:50:30,072 --> 00:50:32,132
and they've recovered all of their advances in publishing

822
00:50:32,172 --> 00:50:34,953
costs paid to you, then the revenue share split

823
00:50:34,973 --> 00:50:37,373
and the back-end payment share split will happen.

824
00:50:37,794 --> 00:50:39,714
And that's when they'll start paying royalties to you.

825
00:50:41,612 --> 00:50:43,995
However, not all publishing contracts are created equal,

826
00:50:44,015 --> 00:50:45,336
so this is something you definitely want

827
00:50:45,376 --> 00:50:46,357
to check in the contract.

828
00:50:47,719 --> 00:50:48,980
And in some worst cases,

829
00:50:49,601 --> 00:50:51,102
and there's plenty of example of publishers

830
00:50:51,122 --> 00:50:51,883
that still do this,

831
00:50:52,564 --> 00:50:55,307
the publisher might look to recover their costs,

832
00:50:55,908 --> 00:50:57,349
including the advances they've paid to you,

833
00:50:57,830 --> 00:50:59,491
from your share of royalties only.

834
00:51:00,944 --> 00:51:02,765
So this is grossly unfair for several reasons,

835
00:51:03,886 --> 00:51:06,288
but namely that one, it ignores all the investment

836
00:51:06,308 --> 00:51:07,309
that you've put into the game

837
00:51:07,329 --> 00:51:08,590
before signing with the publisher.

838
00:51:09,591 --> 00:51:11,392
The publisher makes profit from day one.

839
00:51:12,373 --> 00:51:14,675
It's naturally gonna take you much longer

840
00:51:14,715 --> 00:51:16,096
to receive any backend payments

841
00:51:16,176 --> 00:51:18,679
because the publishers are covering all of their costs

842
00:51:18,699 --> 00:51:20,060
from a smaller pool of revenues.

843
00:51:21,021 --> 00:51:22,502
And last but not least,

844
00:51:22,522 --> 00:51:25,605
but that could also mean that you lead to cashflow issues,

845
00:51:25,985 --> 00:51:28,027
especially if you're relying on these backend payments

846
00:51:28,047 --> 00:51:28,607
to stay afloat.

847
00:51:30,114 --> 00:51:31,755
So while turning down money is hard,

848
00:51:32,296 --> 00:51:34,297
you probably should seriously consider

849
00:51:34,397 --> 00:51:36,699
if a publishing deal is structured in this way

850
00:51:37,139 --> 00:51:38,300
and ask if they will change it

851
00:51:38,800 --> 00:51:40,101
to the model that we've said first.

852
00:51:40,702 --> 00:51:41,983
While it still might not be ideal

853
00:51:42,003 --> 00:51:44,444
that a publisher recovers all of its costs first,

854
00:51:45,045 --> 00:51:48,087
especially if you've incurred significant swept equity

855
00:51:49,268 --> 00:51:50,589
or incurred significant costs

856
00:51:50,709 --> 00:51:51,930
prior to signing with a publisher,

857
00:51:52,510 --> 00:51:54,031
it still means that at least

858
00:51:54,132 --> 00:51:55,533
once the publisher's hit break-even,

859
00:51:55,713 --> 00:51:56,653
you know you're gonna get paid.

860
00:52:00,610 --> 00:52:02,051
So contract killer number seven,

861
00:52:02,251 --> 00:52:04,572
so to finish off, I wanna look at some of the timing issues

862
00:52:05,032 --> 00:52:06,093
that might affect your ability

863
00:52:06,133 --> 00:52:07,973
to carry out your obligations under the contract.

864
00:52:09,234 --> 00:52:10,414
So we've already looked at delays

865
00:52:10,454 --> 00:52:11,875
that might be caused by a publisher

866
00:52:12,355 --> 00:52:14,156
during the evaluation and review of milestones

867
00:52:15,216 --> 00:52:16,897
and the impact that that delay can have on you

868
00:52:17,317 --> 00:52:19,098
in your ability to receive front-end payments.

869
00:52:19,738 --> 00:52:21,979
So now I'll just look a little bit more generally

870
00:52:22,019 --> 00:52:22,819
about what you can do

871
00:52:23,079 --> 00:52:25,000
so that you're not liable for publisher delays.

872
00:52:28,170 --> 00:52:32,335
So plain and simple, you should not be liable for publisher delays or failures.

873
00:52:33,877 --> 00:52:38,923
This should also extend to any third parties or people or individuals or

874
00:52:39,043 --> 00:52:43,689
outsourcers that the publisher requires you to work with, such as porting houses,

875
00:52:43,729 --> 00:52:44,230
for example.

876
00:52:45,025 --> 00:52:50,452
So a publishing contract is there to protect the publisher more than anything.

877
00:52:51,093 --> 00:52:54,798
But that doesn't mean that you need to be penalized for the developer being

878
00:52:55,078 --> 00:52:59,324
delayed or for if any of their parties that they're partners that they're

879
00:52:59,344 --> 00:53:02,007
working with aren't very good or delay or cause failures.

880
00:53:03,436 --> 00:53:06,718
So this is unlikely to be covered in the contractor standard, so you should add it in.

881
00:53:07,359 --> 00:53:10,021
And if there's any publishers listening, then this is a change that you should

882
00:53:10,061 --> 00:53:12,722
definitely consider adding so that it's fair and reasonable.

883
00:53:13,343 --> 00:53:16,725
And that is just ensuring that there's something in the contract that says if

884
00:53:16,745 --> 00:53:20,067
there's any, if there's any delays caused by the publisher and it's not the

885
00:53:20,108 --> 00:53:23,530
developer's fault, the developer's obligations just get extended on a day

886
00:53:23,550 --> 00:53:25,811
for day basis until that delay is rectified.

887
00:53:27,280 --> 00:53:30,321
just means that the developer can pause its obligations

888
00:53:31,462 --> 00:53:32,942
and it doesn't have to fear that it's

889
00:53:32,962 --> 00:53:34,643
going to be a breach of contract for late delivery

890
00:53:34,763 --> 00:53:35,363
or performance.

891
00:53:37,664 --> 00:53:40,364
Now, publishers aren't always at fault for a developer being late

892
00:53:40,444 --> 00:53:41,605
and carrying out its obligations.

893
00:53:43,165 --> 00:53:45,166
In a publishing contract, the obligations for development

894
00:53:45,846 --> 00:53:47,126
ultimately fall on the developer.

895
00:53:48,387 --> 00:53:49,707
But late delivery happens.

896
00:53:49,827 --> 00:53:50,868
Publishers know it happens.

897
00:53:51,668 --> 00:53:53,648
And missing a milestone would normally

898
00:53:53,669 --> 00:53:55,049
be considered a material breach.

899
00:53:56,658 --> 00:54:02,461
But material breaches usually come with a cure period during which time the party at fault can fix any wrongs.

900
00:54:03,161 --> 00:54:08,724
So check the contract to ensure that the contract actually does include a cure period, because it isn't unreasonable to have one.

901
00:54:09,505 --> 00:54:11,786
Especially for late milestone delivery.

902
00:54:12,986 --> 00:54:19,410
You'll normally see if the contract has any cure periods by checking the termination section.

903
00:54:21,271 --> 00:54:25,453
Now a cure period doesn't give you a free pass to deliver builds late.

904
00:54:26,937 --> 00:54:29,098
That's a surefire way to burn bridges with your publisher,

905
00:54:29,639 --> 00:54:31,280
but it is reasonable for you to have time

906
00:54:31,300 --> 00:54:33,201
to fix in areas or late delivery.

907
00:54:36,124 --> 00:54:38,866
And finally, check if timing is of the essence

908
00:54:38,906 --> 00:54:40,667
for delivery of any builds or milestones.

909
00:54:41,348 --> 00:54:42,729
And be careful where a contract states

910
00:54:42,749 --> 00:54:45,331
that delivery of milestones are of the essence.

911
00:54:46,472 --> 00:54:50,893
It's a rather innocuous phrase, but actually it allows the publisher to terminate the agreement

912
00:54:51,194 --> 00:54:52,914
for your breach in the event of late delivery.

913
00:54:53,635 --> 00:54:55,896
And cure periods won't matter or apply on that.

914
00:54:56,416 --> 00:54:59,337
So it's a very powerful right and not really appropriate.

915
00:55:00,718 --> 00:55:01,618
So how do you fix it?

916
00:55:02,338 --> 00:55:06,480
Well, step one, just ask for it to be amended so that missed milestones are material, but

917
00:55:06,520 --> 00:55:07,801
they're not of the essence.

918
00:55:08,561 --> 00:55:11,242
This allows you to benefit from the cure periods we've just discussed.

919
00:55:12,732 --> 00:55:14,413
So where a publisher won't amend this clause,

920
00:55:14,913 --> 00:55:17,273
then the way around it is just to deliver something

921
00:55:17,793 --> 00:55:19,634
on or before the set milestone delivery date.

922
00:55:20,314 --> 00:55:21,554
It doesn't need to be a complete build

923
00:55:21,934 --> 00:55:23,855
and it might not pass the evaluation process,

924
00:55:24,435 --> 00:55:25,495
but it will avoid the publisher

925
00:55:25,515 --> 00:55:27,596
from being able to terminate for late delivery.

926
00:55:28,576 --> 00:55:30,136
So if there are any publishers listening,

927
00:55:31,537 --> 00:55:33,717
just consider removing time of the essence requirements

928
00:55:33,957 --> 00:55:34,718
out of your contract.

929
00:55:35,338 --> 00:55:36,458
Any developer with a good lawyer

930
00:55:36,938 --> 00:55:37,958
is gonna know how to get around it.

931
